WEBVTT

00:00:01.280 --> 00:00:04.320
<v Speaker 1>What was I am from Estar?

00:00:04.320 --> 00:00:07.280
<v Speaker 1>I am Astoy.

00:00:07.280 --> 00:00:08.240
<v Speaker 1>Estoy.

00:00:08.240 --> 00:00:11.200
<v Speaker 1>If you want to say I'm there for you,

00:00:10.940 --> 00:00:14.059
<v Speaker 1>I'm there for you, you know, in this uh supportive way.

00:00:14.059 --> 00:00:16.540
<v Speaker 1>You don't have to say there to begin with.

00:00:16.540 --> 00:00:22.619
<v Speaker 1>Because we are using a star and not sir, it kind of makes that there a little redundant.

00:00:22.619 --> 00:00:23.580
<v Speaker 1>We feel that

00:00:23.660 --> 00:00:28.619
<v Speaker 1>already in a star that's referring to states, locations and states.

00:00:28.619 --> 00:00:33.260
<v Speaker 1>So we don't need to say there, we can just say I'm for you.

00:00:33.260 --> 00:00:35.739
<v Speaker 1>I'm for you using a star.

00:00:35.739 --> 00:00:37.980
<v Speaker 1>What four do you think you need?

00:00:38.600 --> 00:00:39.399
<v Speaker 2>Para.

00:00:39.399 --> 00:00:39.960
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:00:39.960 --> 00:00:43.160
<v Speaker 1>So how do you say I'm there for you talking to a friend?

00:00:44.760 --> 00:00:46.360
<v Speaker 2>Estoy para ti.

00:00:46.360 --> 00:00:47.559
<v Speaker 1>Estoy para ti.

00:00:47.720 --> 00:00:49.000
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:00:48.340 --> 00:00:53.379
<v Speaker 1>To say I'm here because of you, then we are not going to use para.

00:00:53.379 --> 00:00:55.300
<v Speaker 1>We don't even really need to say here

00:00:55.860 --> 00:00:58.740
<v Speaker 2>If it's still a story, it still implies location.

00:00:58.740 --> 00:01:00.260
<v Speaker 1>It kind of just gives you the feeling.

00:01:00.260 --> 00:01:04.739
<v Speaker 1>Actually when you knock on somebody's door and you are calling for them, you will just say Estás.

00:01:04.739 --> 00:01:06.180
<v Speaker 1>You don't say are you there?

00:01:06.180 --> 00:01:10.660
<v Speaker 1>Or if you're on internet, Estas, you will write in the messenger.

00:01:10.340 --> 00:01:15.540
<v Speaker 1>If you call somebody up and you want to speak to Juan, you will not say is Juan there.

00:01:15.540 --> 00:01:17.380
<v Speaker 1>You will just say está Juan.

00:01:17.380 --> 00:01:18.820
<v Speaker 1>Juan está.

00:01:18.820 --> 00:01:22.740
<v Speaker 1>So I am here because of you, Fumel.

00:01:24.120 --> 00:01:25.800
<v Speaker 2>Estoy por usted.

00:01:25.800 --> 00:01:26.280
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:01:26.280 --> 00:01:27.800
<v Speaker 1>Estoy por usted.

00:01:27.800 --> 00:01:30.680
<v Speaker 1>For you informal.

00:01:30.680 --> 00:01:31.960
<v Speaker 1>Estoy por ti.

00:01:31.960 --> 00:01:33.560
<v Speaker 1>Estoy por ti.

00:01:33.300 --> 00:01:35.140
<v Speaker 1>So this would be because of you.

00:01:35.140 --> 00:01:38.580
<v Speaker 1>How would you say I have come because of you?

00:01:38.580 --> 00:01:40.820
<v Speaker 1>I have come because of you.

00:01:40.820 --> 00:01:41.620
<v Speaker 1>Informan.

00:01:41.620 --> 00:01:43.460
<v Speaker 1>I have come because of you.

00:01:44.799 --> 00:01:46.400
<v Speaker 2>The first bit is e.

00:01:50.799 --> 00:01:56.400
<v Speaker 1>So whenever we want, because of, we want to avoid the temptation to translate por que de.

00:01:56.880 --> 00:01:58.560
<v Speaker 1>Because of.

00:01:58.260 --> 00:02:02.020
<v Speaker 1>Good, so I have come because of you e benido por ti.

00:02:02.020 --> 00:02:07.460
<v Speaker 1>You could also say it is because of you that we have come, for example.

00:02:07.460 --> 00:02:08.819
<v Speaker 1>It is because of you

00:02:08.940 --> 00:02:10.060
<v Speaker 1>that we have come.

00:02:10.060 --> 00:02:14.459
<v Speaker 1>And of course we can make the sentence perfectly if we think it through piece by piece.

00:02:14.459 --> 00:02:16.700
<v Speaker 1>So it is because of you

00:02:18.000 --> 00:02:22.080
<v Speaker 1>Es por ti that we have come.

00:02:24.640 --> 00:02:25.360
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:02:28.080 --> 00:02:30.640
<v Speaker 1>It is because of you that we have come.

00:02:30.640 --> 00:02:31.599
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:02:31.520 --> 00:02:37.680
<v Speaker 1>Another use of por, so we are seeing that por is much more flexible than para.

00:02:37.680 --> 00:02:45.840
<v Speaker 1>Another use of por is if you want to say for in the sense of exchanging this one for that one.

00:02:45.140 --> 00:02:49.860
<v Speaker 1>To exchange something for something else, then also we use por.

00:02:49.860 --> 00:02:53.299
<v Speaker 1>Cambiar, cambiar means to change.

00:02:53.320 --> 00:03:01.960
<v Speaker 1>If you want to say, I would change this one for that one, I would change this one for that one.

00:03:01.960 --> 00:03:06.680
<v Speaker 1>And with this one and that one, let's refer to a masculine theme

00:03:06.640 --> 00:03:10.560
<v Speaker 1>So I would change is the first step.

00:03:10.560 --> 00:03:11.760
<v Speaker 2>Campiaria?

00:03:11.760 --> 00:03:12.480
<v Speaker 1>Uh-huh.

00:03:12.480 --> 00:03:15.200
<v Speaker 1>This one, a masculine thing.

00:03:16.300 --> 00:03:20.620
<v Speaker 1>Este good for that one masculine theme.

00:03:20.620 --> 00:03:21.580
<v Speaker 1>Por ese.

00:03:21.580 --> 00:03:21.900
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:03:21.900 --> 00:03:23.180
<v Speaker 1>Take away the T.

00:03:23.180 --> 00:03:23.740
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:03:23.740 --> 00:03:26.460
<v Speaker 1>Cambiaria Este Por S.

00:03:26.460 --> 00:03:29.820
<v Speaker 1>I would change this one for that one.

00:03:29.340 --> 00:03:34.060
<v Speaker 1>How would you say I would change these ones for those ones?

00:03:34.060 --> 00:03:36.140
<v Speaker 1>Masculine or mixed objects.

00:03:36.140 --> 00:03:39.660
<v Speaker 1>I would change these ones for those ones

00:03:41.220 --> 00:03:44.420
<v Speaker 2>Cambiaria estos por esos.

00:03:44.420 --> 00:03:44.980
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:03:44.980 --> 00:03:48.260
<v Speaker 1>Cambiaria estos por esos.

00:03:48.260 --> 00:03:48.740
<v Speaker 1>Very good.

00:03:48.740 --> 00:03:51.060
<v Speaker 1>What if they were feminine things?

00:03:52.160 --> 00:03:55.760
<v Speaker 2>Cambiaría estas por esas.

00:03:55.760 --> 00:03:56.160
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:03:56.160 --> 00:03:58.800
<v Speaker 1>Cambiaría estas por esas.

00:03:58.800 --> 00:03:59.760
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:03:59.340 --> 00:04:01.740
<v Speaker 1>Would you change these ones for those ones?

00:04:01.740 --> 00:04:05.740
<v Speaker 1>Speaking informally, would you change these ones for those ones?

00:04:05.740 --> 00:04:07.660
<v Speaker 1>Still feminine things.

00:04:08.300 --> 00:04:12.220
<v Speaker 2>Campiarias estas por esas.

00:04:12.220 --> 00:04:12.780
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:04:12.780 --> 00:04:15.260
<v Speaker 1>Cambiarias estas por esas.

00:04:15.260 --> 00:04:17.739
<v Speaker 1>Wouldn't you change these ones for those ones?

00:04:17.739 --> 00:04:19.180
<v Speaker 1>Still feminine?

00:04:20.099 --> 00:04:23.300
<v Speaker 2>No cambiarías estas por esas?

00:04:23.300 --> 00:04:24.419
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:04:24.419 --> 00:04:25.460
<v Speaker 1>Go on.

00:04:26.099 --> 00:04:28.580
<v Speaker 2>¿Por qué no cambiaría?

00:04:33.260 --> 00:04:36.220
<v Speaker 2>Sorry, estas

00:04:36.560 --> 00:04:37.600
<v Speaker 2>For esas.

00:04:37.600 --> 00:04:38.000
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:40.000
<v Speaker 1>We don't want to stop thinking.

00:04:40.000 --> 00:04:43.360
<v Speaker 1>You will be able to relax that, uh, as you go on.

00:04:43.360 --> 00:04:47.520
<v Speaker 1>But at the beginning you want to be very insistent on your thinking.

00:04:47.520 --> 00:04:49.440
<v Speaker 1>So you install correct

00:04:49.620 --> 00:04:52.979
<v Speaker 1>structural habits or grammatical habits.

00:04:52.979 --> 00:04:57.699
<v Speaker 1>We don't really use much grammatical terminology, but everything we're seeing here is grammar, of course.

00:04:57.699 --> 00:04:59.379
<v Speaker 1>It's all structure.

00:04:59.400 --> 00:05:06.680
<v Speaker 1>Ah, something I should mention is that if you're chatting online, if you're practicing your Spanish online, you might see por written as an X

00:05:06.960 --> 00:05:12.319
<v Speaker 1>as a shortcut because por is also what you use in like times tables.

00:05:12.319 --> 00:05:15.520
<v Speaker 1>Ocho por ocho is eight times eight

00:05:15.820 --> 00:05:22.620
<v Speaker 1>So you might see gracias por venir, gracias, exvenir.

00:05:22.620 --> 00:05:30.300
<v Speaker 1>And if you have the habit of writing kisses with an ex, this can be very confusing to Spanish speakers.

00:05:30.240 --> 00:05:40.320
<v Speaker 1>So gracias por venir reminds us in this nice hook that we will hear a lot gracias por venir reminds us that we have two words for four.

00:05:40.320 --> 00:05:40.480
<v Speaker 1>Para

00:05:41.340 --> 00:05:48.860
<v Speaker 1>Something being for you quite uh literally and then por which is much more flexible in meaning.

00:05:48.860 --> 00:05:53.260
<v Speaker 1>The other thing that we learn from the sentence gracias por venir

00:05:54.020 --> 00:06:04.980
<v Speaker 1>Is that after prepositions, so these little group of words we've seen para, por, de, en, con, a

00:06:05.280 --> 00:06:06.640
<v Speaker 1>We've seen quite a few of them.

00:06:06.640 --> 00:06:11.360
<v Speaker 1>Following these words in English we put ing, thank you for coming.

00:06:11.360 --> 00:06:15.920
<v Speaker 1>But in Spanish we just put the two form gracias por venir.

00:06:15.920 --> 00:06:18.320
<v Speaker 1>So how do you say thank you for calling?

00:06:18.320 --> 00:06:20.160
<v Speaker 1>Thank you for calling.

00:06:20.500 --> 00:06:29.300
<v Speaker 1>If you forget call, you can think of uh what's your name or how you called because it's something that people tend to have heard somewhere.

00:06:29.160 --> 00:06:31.480
<v Speaker 2>Gracias por llamar.

00:06:31.480 --> 00:06:31.960
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:06:31.960 --> 00:06:33.320
<v Speaker 1>Gracias por llamar.

00:06:33.320 --> 00:06:37.560
<v Speaker 1>And if you wanted to say thanks for calling me, you could say that as well.

00:06:37.940 --> 00:06:40.659
<v Speaker 2>Gracias por llamarme.

00:06:40.659 --> 00:06:41.060
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:06:41.060 --> 00:06:43.620
<v Speaker 1>Gracias por llamarme.

00:06:43.860 --> 00:06:49.940
<v Speaker 1>So after prepositions, we don't use the ing, we want to resist any temptation.

00:06:49.680 --> 00:06:52.800
<v Speaker 1>to put the ing form after the preposition.

00:06:52.800 --> 00:06:58.960
<v Speaker 1>This is negative language transfer, things that are not the same between English and Spanish.

00:06:58.960 --> 00:07:01.840
<v Speaker 1>What was I am from a star?

00:07:02.440 --> 00:07:03.400
<v Speaker 1>Estoy.

00:07:03.400 --> 00:07:04.120
<v Speaker 1>Estoy.

00:07:04.199 --> 00:07:07.240
<v Speaker 1>You remember how to say tired in Spanish?

00:07:07.879 --> 00:07:09.000
<v Speaker 1>Cansado.

00:07:09.000 --> 00:07:09.560
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:07:09.560 --> 00:07:10.599
<v Speaker 1>Cansado.

00:07:10.599 --> 00:07:12.919
<v Speaker 1>So how do you say I am tired?

00:07:13.699 --> 00:07:15.220
