00:09:45.720 --> 00:09:46.520
<v Speaker 2>Creo.

00:09:46.520 --> 00:09:47.000
<v Speaker 1>Yes.

00:09:47.000 --> 00:09:53.640
<v Speaker 1>So we get this situation occasionally in Spanish that the I form of two different verbs will look the same.

00:09:53.339 --> 00:09:58.459
<v Speaker 1>Creo, of course, could be from creer to believe or from crear to create.

00:09:58.459 --> 00:10:00.380
<v Speaker 1>So I don't believe

00:10:01.940 --> 00:10:03.459
<v Speaker 2>No creo.

00:10:03.459 --> 00:10:04.740
<v Speaker 1>In arguing.

00:10:04.740 --> 00:10:07.860
<v Speaker 1>So to argue in Spanish you can use to discuss.

00:10:07.940 --> 00:10:13.540
<v Speaker 1>This is the most common verb actually that's used for argue.

00:10:13.380 --> 00:10:17.220
<v Speaker 1>discuss is diskultir discutir.

00:10:17.220 --> 00:10:19.300
<v Speaker 2>So what do they use for discuss?

00:10:19.300 --> 00:10:20.820
<v Speaker 1>Ablar mostly.

00:10:20.820 --> 00:10:26.260
<v Speaker 1>But you can use diskutir as well for discuss, but it has a heavy connotation mostly.

00:10:26.260 --> 00:10:26.500
<v Speaker 1>No

00:10:26.800 --> 00:10:31.600
<v Speaker 1>I mean if you argue with your boyfriend or your girlfriend, you use this kutir.

00:10:31.600 --> 00:10:32.720
<v Speaker 1>You say this.

00:10:32.720 --> 00:10:37.920
<v Speaker 1>Arguir, arguir, which is argue, means to argue a point.

00:10:37.560 --> 00:10:39.320
<v Speaker 1>rather than to get in an argument.

00:10:39.320 --> 00:10:42.360
<v Speaker 1>Discutir is more like to get in an argument.

00:10:42.360 --> 00:10:45.160
<v Speaker 1>So it's it's what we can call a false friend.

00:10:45.160 --> 00:10:46.280
<v Speaker 1>Words that look

00:10:46.620 --> 00:10:50.940
<v Speaker 1>Like they are the same, but they have a difference in meaning, and there are a few of them.

00:10:50.940 --> 00:10:54.140
<v Speaker 1>We need to watch out for them between English and Spanish.

00:10:54.140 --> 00:10:59.820
<v Speaker 1>Another example would be actual, which doesn't mean actual, it means current

00:11:00.020 --> 00:11:03.940
<v Speaker 1>No, my trabajo actual, my current job.

